From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: tonytranrp <100391458+tonytranrp@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sun, 14 Jun 2026 22:19:37 -1000
Subject: [PATCH] clang-mg: pin compact aggregate-initialization behavior

A compact struct physically reorders its field declaration order, so positional aggregate init is correctly rejected (it would otherwise bind values to the reordered order) and source-order designated init trips -Wreorder-init-list. Add three granular lit tests pinning this behavior; no compiler change. Decoupling semantic declaration order from physical layout order (the real fix) is deferred.


diff --git a/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-designated-reorder-warning.cpp b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-designated-reorder-warning.cpp
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..bf88c4f65
--- /dev/null
+++ b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-designated-reorder-warning.cpp
@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@
+// Because `compact` rewrites the field DECLARATION order (here {a,b} becomes
+// {b,a} after sorting by descending alignment), designated initializers written
+// in SOURCE order are now "out of declaration order", so C++ trips
+// -Wreorder-init-list. This pins the CURRENT behavior; it is a known rough edge
+// of the decl-chain-reorder approach and is expected to change once semantic
+// declaration order is decoupled from physical layout order.
+// See research/08-reorder-safety-and-do-no-harm.md.
+//
+// RUN: %clang_cc1 -std=c++20 -fcxxmg -fsyntax-only -verify %s
+
+compact struct P {
+  char a;   // align 1
+  double b; // align 8  -> reordered declaration order becomes {b, a}
+};
+
+// Source-order designators .a then .b are out of the reordered decl order {b,a}.
+P p = {.a = 1, .b = 2.0}; // expected-warning {{will be initialized after field 'b'}} expected-note {{previous initialization for field 'a' is here}}
diff --git a/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-positional-rejected.cpp b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-positional-rejected.cpp
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..d2e59046d
--- /dev/null
+++ b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-positional-rejected.cpp
@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@
+// A `compact` struct physically reorders its field declaration order, so
+// positional (non-designated) aggregate initialization is REJECTED: the braced
+// values bind to members in declaration order, which `compact` has changed, so
+// allowing it would silently misinitialize fields. Rejecting it is the correct,
+// safe behavior (it mirrors -frandstruct). Use designated initializers instead.
+//
+// KNOWN LIMITATION: the diagnostic says "randomized" because `compact` currently
+// shares randstruct's IsRandomized machinery and the two cannot be distinguished
+// at this point. A compact-specific message is tracked separately. See
+// research/08-reorder-safety-and-do-no-harm.md.
+//
+// RUN: %clang_cc1 -std=c++20 -fcxxmg -fsyntax-only -verify %s
+
+compact struct P {
+  char a;
+  int b;
+  double c;
+};
+
+// Positional init is rejected (would otherwise bind to the reordered order).
+P p = {1, 2, 3.0}; // expected-error {{can only be initialized with a designated initializer}}
diff --git a/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-value-and-zero-ok.cpp b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-value-and-zero-ok.cpp
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..bb84bda98
--- /dev/null
+++ b/clang/test/CXXMG/compact/compact-init-value-and-zero-ok.cpp
@@ -0,0 +1,15 @@
+// Even though `compact` reorders fields, value-initialization `{}` and a single
+// zero initializer `{0}` do not depend on field order, so they remain allowed
+// (this matches the carve-out for randomized structs in C99 6.7.8p19).
+//
+// RUN: %clang_cc1 -std=c++20 -fcxxmg -fsyntax-only -verify %s
+// expected-no-diagnostics
+
+compact struct P {
+  char a;
+  int b;
+  double c;
+};
+
+P e = {};  // value-initialization: no field-order dependence
+P z = {0}; // single zero initializer is explicitly allowed
